	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Motoka</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">
2. The wards are &quot;<b>working as intended</b>&quot; imho in pve: per spell casted on you, you'll loose one ward (tho i've experienced some &quot;normal&quot; attacks from mobs seem to be considered as spells, i.e. you disperse one real spell casted on you -&gt; 1. message like &quot;your mirror ward has reflected XY's Spell&quot; and at the same time you'll get a 2nd message like &quot;your dispersion ward has dispersed XY's attack&quot;)<br /></div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
My experience is that per spell cast you loos all your wards in 80%. It does not really matter if you reflect the spell or not, the ward is gone in most cases.<br />
<br />
For fighting in groups, that spell counter trigger wards does not matter much because the ward of the other group member (tank usually I guess) is gone. But because you where not target of the initial spell, you kept your ward.<br />
<br />
The ward protects you from the first hit of the mob, when the tank looses aggro. With high avoidance you may easily survive two attacks, which gives the tank enough time for a rescue. The ward protects you from melee hits as well. I don’t know from where you get the information that this is working as intended. I never saw an official statement how it should work. I think it is ‘working as “you” expected’.<br />
<br />
For group combat the current behaviour is acceptable for me because I get the useful effect. From the game mechanic point of few I think it’s not correct (and correct game mechanics has again nothing to do with ‘working as intended’). I think the term should be reserved for developers who like to say: ‘I’m not going to look into the details of this and nothing will be done for the issue in the next two month’ but have only time for writing 3 words.<br />
<br />
<br />
Sorry for ticking off on that phrase. But I really hate it.
                  
		</div>
